NODE_4_length_311031_cov_357.878403	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	260726	261781	.	+	0	ID=MGA_1401;product=methylmalonyl-CoA mutase family protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_001338007.1;;locus_tag=LOCUS_13970;note=WP_001338007.1 methylmalonyl-CoA mutase family protein (Escherichia coli) [pid:99.1%25%2C q_cov:94.9%25%2C s_cov:96.0%25%2C Eval:2.0e-192],COG:COG1884:Sbm Methylmalonyl-CoA mutase%2C N-terminal domain/subunit [Category:I%2C Aligned:5-305%2C Eval:3.9e-155%2C score:444.1%2C C-term missing],Domain:cl28270:ACH1 Acyl-CoA hydrolase [Energy production and conversion]. This family of CoA transferases includes enzymes catalyzing at least two related but distinct activities. The E. coli YgfH protein has been characterized as a propionyl-CoA:succinate CoA transferase where it appears to be involved in a pathway for the decarboxylation of succinate to propionate. The Clostridium kluyveri CAT1 protein has been characterized as a acetyl-CoA:succinate CoA transferase and is believed to be involved in anaerobic succinate degradation. The propionate:succinate transferase activity has been reported in the propionic acid fermentation of propionibacterium species%2C where it is distinct from the coupled activities of distinct nucleotide-triphosphate dependent succinate and propionate/acetate CoA transferases (as inferred from activity in the absence of NTPs). The family represented by this model includes a member from Propionibacterium acnes KPA171202 which is likely to be responsible for this activity. A closely related clade not included in this family are the Ach1p proteins of fungi which are acetyl-CoA hydrolases. This name has been applied to many of the proteins represented by this model%2C possibly erroneously. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:304-351%2C Eval:1.2e-11%2C score:62.8%2C N-term missing],MGA_1401
